'''Dottie West''' (born '''Dorothy Marie Marsh'''; October 11, 1932 – September 4, 1991<ref name="LarkinCountry">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who's Who of Country Music]]|editor-first=Colin|editor-last=Larkin|author-link=Colin Larkin (writer)|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|location=New York City|date=1993|edition=First|isbn=0-85112-726-6|pages=439/440}}</ref>) was an American [[Country music|country]] singer and songwriter. She also had several credits as an actress. A distinguished figure in the country genre, West was among several people who helped to elevate the platform of female country artists. She was also known for mentoring up-and-coming artists and being the first woman to win a country music accolade from the [[Grammy Awards]].

West's exposure to country music in childhood influenced her continued music education at [[Tennessee Tech|Tennessee Polytechnic Institute]]. After marrying, the family moved to Ohio where West made her first appearances singing on regional television. Her aspirations to write and record country led to West getting a [[Starday Records]] recording contract in 1959. West and her family then moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] where she continued recording and releasing unsuccessful singles for Starday. In 1963, West signed with [[RCA Records|RCA Victor]], where she had first success. Her self-penned "[[Here Comes My Baby (Dottie West song)|Here Comes My Baby]]" (1964) became a top ten US country song and won her a Grammy. Writing and co-writing her own material, West had more top ten [[Nashville Sound]]-influenced singles like "[[Would You Hold It Against Me]]", "[[Paper Mansions]]" and "[[Rings of Gold]]".

West continued recording for RCA through 1976, having a [[Crossover music|crossover pop]] single with 1973's "[[Country Sunshine (song)|Country Sunshine]]". The latter was also a [[Coca-Cola]] commercial [[jingle]] that was played routinely on television. Moving to [[United Artists Records]] (which later bought [[Liberty Records]], West had her peak success in her middle age. In the late 1970s, she recorded two albums with [[Kenny Rogers]]. Their first duet "[[Every Time Two Fools Collide (song)|Every Time Two Fools Collide]]" (1978) became her first chart-topping single and was followed by four more top ten songs. The newfound success led to her own solo career reigniting. In 1980, West had her first chart-topping solo single with "[[A Lesson in Leavin']]" and was followed by several more top 20 songs.

In the early 1980s, West began an acting career, appearing on television shows such as ''[[The Love Boat]]'' and films like ''[[The Aurora Encounter]]''. She signed a new recording contract with Permian Records and her last album was released there in 1984. West continued appearing on television and touring. However, her increased spending habits would lead to her filing for [[bankruptcy]] in 1990. Her personal possessions were sold in a public auction by the [[Internal Revenue Service]] and she was forced to sell her home. While in the midst of planning a career comeback, West was killed in a car accident in 1991. Following her death, her life was made into a [[Big Dreams and Broken Hearts: The Dottie West Story|television movie]] and she was inducted into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]].

==Early life==
Dorothy Marie Marsh was born in Frog Pond, Tennessee, a community roughly {{convert|64|mi}} northeast of [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] in Macon County. She was the eldest of ten children born to Pelina Artha ([[née]] Jones) and William Hollis Marsh.<ref name="LarkinCountry"/> Hollis Marsh was a musician who played the guitar and fiddle.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=222}} Pelina Marsh was a homemaker but also worked various odd jobs to support the family.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=22}} Hollis suffered from [[alcoholism]] which caused him to become abusive and unable to hold a job.<ref name="Opry Book">{{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Behind the Grand Ole Opry Curtain |date=2008 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group|Center Street Publishing]] |isbn=978-1599951843 |chapter=3: A Lesson in Leavin'}}</ref> The Marsh family lived a reportedly impoverished life, often running out of food and other resources.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=20&ndash;25}}<ref name="UPI">{{cite news |title=Dottie West dies on operating table |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1991/09/04/Dottie-West-dies-on-operating-table/7677683956800/ |access-date=28 October 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=September 4, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Simmonds |first1=Jeremy |title=The Encyclopedia of Dead Rock Stars Heroin, Handguns, and Ham Sandwiches |date=2012 |publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]] |isbn=978-1613744789 |page=277}}</ref> In Dorothy's early years, the family lived in dilapidated homes. At one point a new home was being constructed by Pelina's extended family but was burnt to the ground by Hollis before its completion.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=24}}

Hollis Marsh was drafted during [[World War II]] but was discharged after three months. The family received military [[Subscription (finance)|allotment]] checks which provided enough financial stability to build their own home.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=39-45}} Pelina Marsh then took on a job at a tree nursery to provide for her children. Being the oldest child, Dorothy took on the responsibility of caring for her younger siblings while her mother worked.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=45-46}} Dorothy and Pelina also worked in the fields of their neighbor's farm, picking fruits and vegetables.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=49}} At age 12, Dorothy raised money through a school fundraiser to buy her first guitar.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=54-55}}

During her teen years, Dorothy attended Central High School in [[McMinnville, Tennessee]].{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=64&ndash;65}} During this period, her father continued abusing alcohol and physically abusing his children including Dorothy. On some occasions, Hollis Marsh would hold his wife and children at gunpoint.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=62-63}} Around age 11, Dorothy began being repeatedly molested by her father. Too afraid to report it, the abuse continued for several years. She never spoke of the abuse during her lifetime. As a result of her father's sexual abuse, Dorothy had a [[miscarriage]] at age 15.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}}

At age 17, her father had found a job working for the [[Ford Motor Company]] in [[Detroit, Michigan]]. He threatened to take Dorothy out of school so she could move to Detroit with him. After being told the news by her father, Dorothy became uncontrollably emotional at school.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=64&ndash;65}} The same day, she confessed the molestation to her high school teachers.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} Hollis Marsh was then arrested on rape and incest charges. Dorothy subsequently went to live with the county sheriff for several weeks while her mother moved the family into a McMinnville apartment.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=65&ndash;67}} Dorothy later testified in court against her father.<ref name="Medium">{{cite web |last1=Snaith |first1=Holly |title=Dottie West: Raised on Country Sunshine |url=https://medium.com/music-voices/dottie-west-raised-on-country-sunshine-b541ce1e594b |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |date=September 5, 2022 |access-date=28 October 2023}}</ref> Hollis was ultimately found guilty of all charges and sentenced to 40 years at [[Tennessee State Prison]]. He eventually died in prison in 1967.<ref name="Sun Sentinel">{{Cite web|first=Deborah|last=Walker|date=January 17, 1995|title=Dottie West TV Film Doesn't Do Her Wrong|newspaper=[[Sun Sentinel]]|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1995-01-18-9501170285-story.html|access-date=May 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201211853/https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1995-01-18-9501170285-story.html|archive-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}}{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=67}}

Dorothy eventually moved back into her mother's McMinnville apartment. Her mother had to go on [[welfare]] to support her family. Along with her mother, Dorothy became a waitress at a local restaurant.<ref name="Opry Book"/> Her mother eventually moved the family into a house and opened up her own restaurant in McMinnville.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=72&ndash;73}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goldsmith|first1=Thomas|title=Legendary Dottie West Dies|work=[[USA Today]]|date=September 4, 1991}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Ankeny |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/dottie-west-mn0000190632/biography |title=Dottie West &#124; Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> During this time, Dorothy began going by the name of Dottie. She also began singing and playing guitar in a high school band called The Coonskins.<ref name="Opry Book"/> The group played at high school events and also at square dances, picnics and other local events.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|pp=69&ndash;70}} Following high school graduation, a McMinnville businessman got Dottie a music scholarship to attend [[Tennessee Tech|Tennessee Polytechnic Institute]]. During her first day, Dottie met fellow student and [[steel guitar]] player Bill West{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=75}} whom she later married. As a result, she changed her name to Dottie West.<ref name="Tennessean">{{Cite news|last=Thanki|first=Juli|title=Country trailblazer Dottie West remembered|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/08/26/country-trailblazer-dottie-west-remembered/88531556/|date=August 26, 2016|access-date=May 27, 2021|newspaper=[[The Tennessean]]}}</ref>

==Career==
===1956–1962: Regional TV in Ohio and beginnings in Nashville===
In 1956, the West family moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''The Country Girl Singing Sensation'' (LP Liner Notes) |journal=[[Starday Records]] |date=May 1964 |id=SLP-302}}</ref> Bill West found work in a steel facility and Dottie obtained a five-year contract on the regional country music television program ''Landmark Jamboree''.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} On the show, West formed a singing duo called The Kay-Dots with Kathy Dee.<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web |title=Dottie West |url=https://www.countrymusichalloffame.org/hall-of-fame/dottie-west |website=[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] |access-date=4 November 2023}}</ref> The ''Landmark Jamboree'' often had mainstream country artists appear including [[The Carter Sisters]], whom West met later worked with.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} West also had aspirations of mainstream country stardom herself. Along with her husband and children, the family spent numerous weekends traveling to Nashville, Tennessee where she attempted to score a recording contract.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/><ref name="Medium"/><ref name="autogenerated1"/> On one 1959 trip, West went into every Nashville record label but still could not get signed. Feeling discouraged, the family was about to drive back to Cleveland when they spotted the office of [[Starday Records]]. Auditioning live for Starday's Don Pierce, she was signed to the label on the spot.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=78}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}}

One week later, West self-financed $511 to record her first Starday [[Single (music)|single]] titled "An Angel on Paper".{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=78}} The single, along with several further releases, failed to gain commercial success.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> However, "An Angel on Paper" did receive occasional local Nashville airplay. Ott Devine of the Grand Ole Opry heard the song and had West make her debut appearance on the show in 1960. She traveled with her family for several more sporadic Opry appearances during the year. After saving nearly a $1000, the West family officially moved to Nashville in 1961. They temporarily lived with West's in-laws before finding their own small house in West Nashville.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=79}} The same year, West was hired by booking agent Lucky Moeller who arranged her first tours and shows in the United States.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=79-80}}

During this period, West and her husband met aspiring Nashville songwriters [[Hank Cochran]], [[Red Lane]], [[Roger Miller]], [[Willie Nelson]] and [[Justin Tubb]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} The family often brought songwriters back to their home where West would cook for them and in return learn to write songs.<ref name="Opry Book"/><ref name="Tennessean 2016">{{cite news |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Country Trailblazer Dottie West Remembered |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/08/26/country-trailblazer-dottie-west-remembered/88531556/ |access-date=4 November 2023 |work=[[The Tennessean|Tennessean]] |date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> West also became close friends with [[Patsy Cline]] during this time.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Struggling financially, Cline on occasion brought the West's on the road with her to help provide work.<ref name="Wide Open Country">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Addie |title=Dottie West: A Country Music Success Story With a Tragic Ending |url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/dottie-west/ |website=Wide Open Country |date=March 17, 2020 |access-date=4 November 2023}}</ref> West also toured with several other Grand Ole Opry performers and was now being managed by the Jim Denny Artist Bureau. In July 1962, moved to [[Atlantic Records]], becoming the label's first country music artist on the roster.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Atlantic in C&W with Dottie West |magazine=Music Reporter |date=July 14, 1962 |page=19 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Music-Business/Music-Reporter-1962-07-14.pdf |access-date=4 November 2023}}</ref> However, the label also failed to generate any commercial success for her.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/>

According to West, the first song she ever wrote was "Is This Me?". She then recorded a [[Demo (music)|demonstration tape]] with the help of steel guitarist [[Pete Drake]].<ref name="Opry Book"/> "Is This Me?" was heard by [[Jim Reeves]] who chose to record it. Released as a single, the song became a commercial success for Reeves in 1963.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223-224}} Reeves liked West's singing voice and brought her to the attention of [[Chet Atkins]] of [[RCA Records|RCA Victor records]]. Atkins signed her to his label shortly afterward. "Dottie was the best female singer in town [Nashville] and everybody knew it," he later said.<ref name="Opry Book"/>

===1963–1968: "Here Comes My Baby" and success at RCA Victor===
West's first RCA Victor recordings were released as singles in 1963: "[[Touch Me (Willie Nelson song)|Touch Me]]"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title="[[Touch Me (Willie Nelson song)|Touch Me]]"/"More Than I Meant To" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor Records]] |date=April 1963 |id=47-8166}}</ref> and "[[Let Me off at the Corner]]".<ref name="Single">{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title="[[Let Me off at the Corner]]"/"I Wish You Wouldn't Do That" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=August 1963 |id=47-8225}}</ref> The latter became her first to make the US country chart<ref name="autogenerated1"/> reaching number 29.<ref name="Country Songs">{{cite magazine |title=Dottie West chart history (Country Songs) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/dottie-west/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=11 November 2023}}</ref> Her next release "[[Love Is No Excuse]]" was a duet with Jim Reeves that reached the top ten.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Yet it was the next single that was considered West's breakthrough solo recording: "[[Here Comes My Baby (Dottie West song)|Here Comes My Baby]]".<ref name="Hall of Fame"/><ref name="Medium"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} Co-written by West and her husband,<ref name="Medium"/> it reached number ten on the US country chart in late 1964.<ref name="Country Songs"/> "Here Comes My Baby" led to West winning the first-ever [[Grammy Award|Grammy award]] given to a female country artist<ref name="NY Times">{{cite news |title=Dottie West, 58; Country Singer Won Top Vocalist Award |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/05/obituaries/dottie-west-58-country-singer-won-top-vocalist-award.html |access-date=11 November 2023 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 5, 1991}}</ref> and a membership to the [[Grand Ole Opry]].<ref name="autogenerated1"/> "Here Comes My Baby" was then included on West's debut studio album of the [[Here Comes My Baby (album)|same name]] (1965), which was produced by Chet Atkins and included five self-composed songs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''Here Comes My Baby'' (Liner Notes -- Vinyl insert) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=June 1965 |id=LSP-3368}}</ref> The disc reached number 12 on the US country albums chart, as did her next studio album ''[[Dottie West Sings]]''.<ref name="Country Albums">{{cite magazine |title=Dottie West chart history (Country Albums) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/dottie-west/chart-history/csi/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=11 November 2023}}</ref> Her follow-up singles reached the US country top 40 through 1966: "[[Didn't I (Dottie West song)|Didn't I]]", "[[Gettin' Married Has Made Us Strangers]]", "[[No Sign of Living]]" and "[[Before the Ring on Your Finger Turns Green]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/>
[[file:Dottie West--1960s (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|West {{circa}} 1965]]

By this point, West was being highlighted by critics for her "heart-wrenching" self-penned lyrics and her emotional vocal performances.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} Her third album ''[[Suffer Time]]'' (1966) was conceptualized from West's new musical style. The characters of its songs were often victims of heartache and failing relationships.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}}<ref name="Suffer Time Liner Notes and Al">{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''Suffer Time'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=July 1966 |id=LSP-3587}}</ref> The disc was her highest-charting yet, reaching number three on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> It also spawned four chart singles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Suffer Time'': Dottie West: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/suffer-time-mw0000871136 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=12 November 2023}}</ref> The second single, "[[Would You Hold It Against Me]]", reached the top five of the US country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> With [[Chet Atkins]] still serving as West's producer, the pair recorded three studio albums that were issued in 1967: ''[[With All My Heart and Soul (album)|With All My Heart and Soul]]'', ''[[Dottie West Sings Sacred Ballads]]'' and ''[[I'll Help You Forget Her]]''.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> ''With All My Heart and Soul'' reached the US country top ten while ''I'll Help You Forget Her'' charted at number 11.<ref name="Country Albums"/> The albums included the top ten single "[[Paper Mansions]]" and the top 20 single "[[Like a Fool (Dottie West song)|Like a Fool]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/>

Now in popular demand, West formed her own touring band called The Heartaches. It featured Bill West on [[steel guitar]], along with Bobby Taylor, Ray Wix and Danny Shannon. West and The Heartaches toured frequently across the United States and Canada, often performing at state fairs, auditoriums and occasionally headlining venues like the Black Poodle Club in Nashville.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=93-94}} Her 1967 album ''[[The Sound of Country Music]]'' gave dual credit to West and her new band.<ref name="Liner Notes">{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''The Sound of Country Music'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) [credited as Dottie West and the Heartaches] |journal=[[RCA Camden]] |date=February 1967 |id=CAS-2155}}</ref> West also appeared in two country music-themed films during this time: ''Second Fiddle to a Steel Guitar'' and ''There's a Still on the Hill''.<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite book |last1=Stambler |first1=Irwin |last2=Landon |first2=Grelun |title=Country Music: The Encyclopedia |date=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |isbn=9780312264871 |pages=526–527}}</ref> RCA continued releasing new material of West's as well. In 1968, the label released the studio LP's ''[[What I'm Cut Out to Be]]'', ''[[Country Girl (Dottie West album)|Country Girl]]'' and ''[[Feminine Fancy]]''. All three discs reached the US country albums chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> The same year, the singles "[[Country Girl (Dottie West song)|Country Girl]]" and "[[Reno (Dottie West song)|Reno]]" became US top 20 country songs<ref name="Country Songs"/> and top ten songs on the Canadian country chart.<ref name="RPM Country Singles">{{cite web|title=Search results for ''Dottie West'' under "country singles"|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=gmrhouli7kvfvaeu848ka389j0&q1=Dottie+West&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|access-date=1 April 2011}}</ref>

===1969–1976: Collaborations, "Country Sunshine" and commercial decline===
As West's career progressed, she was chosen as a collaborator on duets for male country artists.<ref name="Ten Best">{{cite web |title=The 10 Best Dottie West Songs, Ranked |url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/dottie-west-songs-ranked/ |website=Wide Open Country |date=October 11, 2021 |access-date=26 November 2023}}</ref> She first collaborated with [[Don Gibson]] on several duet recordings that were released on the 1969 album ''[[Dottie and Don]]''. The project was her final with Chet Atkins.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Their first collaborative single was 1969's "[[Rings of Gold]]", which reached number two on the US country chart<ref name="Country Songs"/> and topped the Canadian country chart.<ref name="RPM Country Singles"/> It was followed by "[[Sweet Memories (song)|Sweet Memories]]" (later recorded by [[Willie Nelson]])<ref>{{cite book |last1=Streissguth |first1=Michael |title=Always Been There Rosanne Cash, The List, and the Spirit of Southern Music |date=2009 |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |isbn=978-0306818523 |page=28}}</ref> and "[[There's a Story (Goin' 'Round)]]". The latter was a top ten country single in the US.<ref name="Country Songs"/> In 1971, she joined [[Jimmy Dean]] on the single "[[Slowly (song)|Slowy]]",<ref name="Opry Book"/> which made the US country top 30.<ref name="Country Songs"/> The duo also recorded an album of duets which was titled ''[[Country Boy & Country Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dean |first1=Jimmy |last2=West |first2=Dottie |title=''[[Country Boy & Country Girl]]'' (Album Information/Liner Notes) |journal=[[RCA Victor]] |date=November 1970 |id=LSP-4434}}</ref> Together, Dean and West played the ''[[Landmark (hotel and casino)|Landmark]]'' and ''[[Golden Nugget Las Vegas|Golden Nugget]]'' hotels in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]].<ref name="Opry Book"/>

West also continued recording solo material.<ref name="Opry Book"/> Between 1970 and 1972, RCA Victor released the charting singles "Clingin' to My Baby's Hand", "[[Careless Hands]]", "Lonely Is" and "I'm Only a Woman". Among the highest-charting was 1970's "[[Forever Yours (Dottie West song)|Forever Yours]]", which climbed to number 21 on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Its [[Forever Yours (Dottie West album)|corresponding studio album]] reached the US country top 40.<ref name="Country Albums"/> By the early 1970s, critics noticed an increasing emotional vocal delivery from West on her recordings. [[Robert K. Oermann]] and Mary A. Bufwack wrote that West developed a "moaning quality that she began using to great emotional effect".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} [[AllMusic]]'s Bill Carpenter found her 1971 single "Six Weeks Every Summer (Christmas Every Other Year)" to have both "substance" and "passion".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carpenter |first1=Bill |title=''The Essential Dottie West'': Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-essential-dottie-west-mw0000182759 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=26 November 2023}}</ref> In the latter (whose story line is based on a single mother), West reportedly cried during its recording session.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} This was followed by the top 30 US country single "[[If It's All Right with You]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/> It was included on West's 1973 [[If It's All Right with You/Just What I've Been Looking For|studio album]], which featured West's new husband Byron Metcalf on the cover.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''If It's All Right with You/Just What I've Been Looking For'' (Liner Notes/Album Information) |journal=[[RCA Victor]] |date=May 1973 |id=APL1-0151}}</ref>

In the early 1970s, [[Coca-Cola]] advertising executives heard West's 1968 song "Country Girl". In turn, West agreed to compose and record commercial jingles for Coca-Cola.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Dottie West |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 29, 1972 |volume=78 |issue=31}}</ref> In 1972, the company adapted "Country Girl" into a jingle that was played routinely as a television commercial. As a result, the company gave West a lifetime contract to make jingles for Coke. A follow-up jingle was co-written with [[Billy Davis (songwriter)|Billy Davis]] called "[[Country Sunshine (song)|Country Sunshine]]".<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> The [[McCann (company)|McCann Ericson]] television commercial had become so popular with audiences that it was adapted into a RCA Victor single.<ref name="Medium"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Country Commercials |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1981/03/30/COUNTRY-COMMERCIALS/5700354776400/ |access-date=19 November 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=March 30, 1981}}</ref> Released in 1973, the single version reached number two on the US country chart<ref name="Country Songs"/> and crossed over to number 49 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].<ref name="Hot 100">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Top Pop Singles 1955–2010|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2011|isbn=978-0-89820-188-8}}</ref> It also made similar positions in Canada.<ref name="RPM Country Singles"/><ref name="RPM Top Singles">{{cite web|title=Search results for ''Dottie West'' under "top singles"|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=gmrhouli7kvfvaeu848ka389j0&q1=Dottie+West&q2=Top+Singles&interval=20|publisher=RPM|access-date=1 April 2011}}</ref> A studio album of the [[Country Sunshine (Dottie West album)|same name]] made it to number 17 on the US country albums chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/>

In 1974, West had a second US top ten country single with "[[Last Time I Saw Him (song)|Last Time I Saw Him]]". Her follow-up releases failed to gain the same momentum and West's commercial popularity began declining.<ref name="Medium"/> Her next studio album ''[[House of Love (Dottie West album)|House of Love]]''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''House of Love'' (Album Notes/Liner Notes) |journal=[[RCA Victor]] |date=May 1974 |id=APL1-0543}}</ref> spawned two top 40 singles: the [[House of Love (Dottie West song)|title track]] and "[[Lay Back Lover]]". However, further singles released through 1976 reached positions outside the US country top 40.<ref name="Country Songs"/> West's final RCA album ''[[Carolina Cousins]]'' (1975) only reached number 45 on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> In 1976, West departed the RCA Victor roster.<ref name="Medium"/><ref name="Encyclopedia"/>

===1976–1983: Duets with Kenny Rogers and solo comeback===
In 1976, West signed with [[United Artists Records]]<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> and started recording with [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=356}} Her first label release was the top 20 US and Canadian country single "[[When It's Just You and Me]]" (1976).<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Singles"/> Its [[When It's Just You and Me (album)|album of the same name]] made the US country top 50.<ref name="Country Albums"/> It also spawned the top 40 songs "[[Every Word I Write]]" and "[[Tonight You Belong to Me]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/> Following this, West was putting finishing touches on a new track called "[[Every Time Two Fools Collide (song)|Every Time Two Fools Collide]]" when her session was interrupted by [[Kenny Rogers]] (who was waiting to use the studio next). After informally singing the song together, the pair realized it could be a duet. Ultimately, it was decided the track would be cut as a duet.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/><ref name="Gazette">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Doug |title=Now There Was A Song |url=https://www.texarkanagazette.com/news/2023/jun/08/every-time-two-fools-collide-an-accidental-on/ |access-date=10 December 2023 |work=[[Texarkana Gazette]] |date=June 8, 2023}}</ref> In 1978, their duet version of "Every Time Two Fools Collide" became West's first number one US country single.<ref name="Country Songs"/> The pair then released two studio albums of duets: ''[[Every Time Two Fools Collide]]'' (1978) and ''[[Classics (Kenny Rogers and Dottie West album)|Classics]]'' (1979).<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> Both discs became the first in West's career to sell half a million copies, receiving certifications from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web |title=Gold & Platinum: Dottie West |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=dottie+west#search_section |website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |access-date=10 December 2023}}</ref>

The duo's collaborative success resulted in West's own commercial resurgence.<ref name="RG">{{cite book|last1=Wolff|first1=Kurt|title=Country Music: The Rough Guide|date=2000|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=1-85828-534-8 |page=427}}</ref> The pairing had three more top ten and chart-topping country singles through 1979: "[[Anyone Who Isn't Me Tonight]]", "[[All I Ever Need Is You (song)|All I Ever Need Is You]]" and "[['Til I Can Make It on My Own]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Singles"/> For the first time in her career, West headlined sports arenas and large concert venues.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> This included Rogers and West co-hosting an [[NBC]] television special dubbed "The World's Largest Indoor Country Music Show" and included 60,000 fans.<ref name="Opry Book"/> Alongside Rogers, she also made some of her first appearances on nationally televised programs including ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]''.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> In 1978 and 1979, the pair won back-to-back [[Country Music Association Award for Vocal Duo of the Year|Vocal Duo of the Year]] accolades from the [[Country Music Association Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=CMA Past Winners: Dottie West |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=349ITR1626D7WTN4MOE8Z4Y3QOK8QAMX8Q9NDHTK615W3VF9MR0PXD5VV2Y062CP67TA8502R034V194Q3LW993ZA27851R5OPJ6CVTFTK46535F377WUQ0572369WSG |website=[[Country Music Association]] |access-date=10 December 2023}}</ref> West also made changes to her image by getting [[plastic surgery]] and purchasing $100,000 [[spandex]] outfits designed by [[Bob Mackie]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=356}}

Although finding renewed popularity as a duo, West's solo material was failing to have the same commercial momentum.<ref name="Billboard Article">{{cite magazine |last1=Kirby |first1=Kip |title=Dottie West Ventures into Pop Field with Newest LP |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=November 24, 1979 |pages=37–43 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Music/Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-11-24.pdf |access-date=3 December 2023}}</ref><ref name="Encyclopedia"/> She became increasingly frustrated with the lack of "excitement" in her solo recordings. Ultimately, West decided to make changes to both her management and musical style. In 1979, she signed with Rogers' management team, Kragen and Co.<ref name="Billboard Article"/> She also replaced Larry Butler with the newly-established record producers [[Randy Goodrum]] and [[Brent Maher]].<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> The Goodrum-Maher pair produced and wrote songs for West. Together, they reworked her musical style to help her identify with contemporary audiences. The result was West's 1979 album ''[[Special Delivery (Dottie West album)|Special Delivery]]''.<ref name="Billboard Article"/> Critics took notice of its neapproach and found it to incorporate a [[Soul music|soul]] influence.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Cantwell |first1=David |title=10 Classic Country Albums Turning 40 in 2019 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 21, 2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country-lists/10-classic-country-albums-turning-40-in-2019-838076/dottie-west-special-delivery-united-artists-838222/ |access-date=3 December 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Roland |first1=Tom |title=''Special Delivery'': Dottie West: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/special-delivery-mw0000871766 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=3 December 2023}}</ref> The disc climbed to number 13 on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> From the disc, came the top 20 US country singles "[[You Pick Me Up (And Put Me Down)]]" and "[[Leavin's for Unbelievers]]". Its most successful 1980's "[[A Lesson in Leavin']]", which became the first solo single in West's career to top the US country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="Billboard Article"/><ref name="Encyclopedia"/>

Now in her late forties, West had reached the peak of her career.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=357}} She was now a solo concert headline, often doing close to 300 dates a year.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> In 1980, West had her own television special which aired on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] network, also titled ''Special Delivery''.<ref name="Special Delivery">{{cite magazine |last1=Skates |first1=Sarah |title=Hall of Fame Highlights Dottie West |magazine=[[MusicRow]] |date=March 14, 2013 |url=https://musicrow.com/2013/03/hall-of-fame-highlights-dottie-west/ |access-date=10 December 2023}}</ref> [[Liberty Records]] released her next studio project called ''[[Wild West (album)|Wild West]]'' (1981).<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> Featuring her wearing skin tight pants and a cowgirl hat on the cover,{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=225}} it climbed to the number five position on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'' praised its song selection and believed it to have [[crossover music|crossover]] potential.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=COUNTRY: Album Reviews |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=February 21, 1981 |page=27 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/80s/1981/CB-1981-02-21-OCR-Page-0027.pdf#search=%22dottie%20west%20wild%20west%20review%22 |access-date=10 December 2023}}</ref> Spawned from the album was "[[Are You Happy Baby?]]", West's second solo single to reach the number one spot. It was followed by another chart-topper called "[[What Are We Doin' in Love]]" (a duet with Kenny Rogers).<ref name="Country Songs"/> The latter crossed over into the pop field, becoming her highest-charting song on the US Hot 100, peaking at number 14 in 1981.<ref name="Hot 100"/> It also made the Canadian country top five and Canadian adult contemporary top ten.<ref name="RPM Country Singles"/><ref name="RPM AC Singles">{{cite web|title=Search results for ''Dottie West'' under "adult contemporary"|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=gmrhouli7kvfvaeu848ka389j0&q1=Dottie+West&q2=Adult+Contemporary&interval=20|publisher=RPM|accessdate=1 April 2011}}</ref>

In 1982, West co-hosted the [[17th Academy of Country Music Awards]] alongside [[Mickey Gilley]] and [[Conway Twitty]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Jeff |title=The band Alabama rode their hit album 'Feels So... |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/04/29/The-band-Alabama-rode-their-hit-album-Feels-So/3291388900800/ |access-date=10 December 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=April 29, 1982}}</ref> In 1983, West (who was a lifelong active [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]) performed on the party's syndicated telethon "Celebrate America".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1983/05/28/democrats-hope-to-get-6-million-in-telethon/12f1abe7-6358-49b4-ac9a-9934c56751b3/|title=Democrats Hope to Get $6 Million in Telethon|first=Jay|last=Mathews|date=May 28, 1983|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Along with more television appearances, West started to dabble in acting. She appeared on an episode of ''[[The Love Boat]]'',<ref name="Love Boat">{{cite news |title=LOVE BOAT 'COUNTRY' |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/04/11/LOVE-BOAT-COUNTRY/7600418885200/ |access-date=10 December 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=April 11, 1983}}</ref> and played the voice of Melissa Raccoon in the film ''[[The Raccoons and the Lost Star]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Premiering This Week |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |date=July 1984 |volume=32 |page=113}}</ref> She also portrayed Mona in the traveling stage production of ''[[The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas]]''.<ref name="Music City News">{{cite magazine |last1=Dixon Harden |first1=Lydia |title=New Projects Keep Dottie West Going |magazine=Music City News |date=1983 |pages=62–63}}</ref> At age 50, West shot a photo spread for the adult magazine ''[[Oui (magazine)|Oui]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Delaney |first1=Kelly |title=Dottie West |magazine=Inside Country Music News |date=February 1983 |page=63}}</ref> The same year, the single "[[It's High Time]]" reached the US country top 20.<ref name="Country Songs"/> It was the lead release off her 1981 studio album ''[[High Times (Dottie West album)|High Time]]'', which made the US country top 50.<ref name="Country Albums"/> In 1982, the Liberty label released the album ''[[Full Circle (Dottie West album)|Full Circle]]'', which was produced by [[Larry Gatlin]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flint |first1=Joseph H. |last2=Nelson |first2=Judy A. |title=The Insider's Country Music Handbook |date=1993 |publisher=[[Gibbs Smith]] |isbn=978-0879055639 |page=414}}</ref> West's second TV special aired on Showtime in 1982 and was also named ''Full Circle''.<ref name="Full Circle">{{cite magazine |title=West Special on Showtime |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=August 21, 1982 |volume=94 |issue=33 |page=37 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1yQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=dottie+west+full+circle+TV+special+showtime&pg=PT36 |access-date=10 December 2023}}</ref> Her final Liberty album was released in 1983 titled ''[[New Horizons (Dottie West album)|New Horizons]]'', which only reached the US country top 70.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Both ''Full Circle'' and ''New Horizons'' spawned West's final top 40 singles: "[[You're Not Easy to Forget]]", "[[She Can't Get My Love off the Bed]]" and "[[Tulsa Ballroom]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/>

===1984–1991: Final years===
In 1984, West signed a five-year recording contract with Permian Records.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Allen |first1=Sharon |title=Nashville This Week |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |date=November 8, 1984 |page=43 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/80s/84/RR-1984-11-09-OCR-Page-0043.pdf#search=%22dottie%20west%20permian%20records%201984%22 |access-date=17 December 2023}}</ref> She collaborated with producer [[Jerry Crutchfield]] on her first label album<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Allen |first1=Sharon |title=West in Alien Flick? |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |date=November 9, 1984 |page=43 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/80s/84/RR-1984-11-09-OCR-Page-0043.pdf#search=%22dottie%20west%20permian%20records%201984%22 |access-date=17 December 2023}}</ref> titled ''[[Just Dottie]]'' (1984). ''Billboard'' found it both "sorrowful" and "sassy",<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Billboard Album Reviews |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 6, 1984 |volume=96 |issue=38 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MyQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=dottie+west+permian+records+just+dottie+1984&pg=PT82 |access-date=17 December 2023}}</ref> while ''[[The Tennessean]]'' found the disc to have "powerful women lyrics".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Glamorous Dottie West Remains a Role Model |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=November 10, 1984}}</ref> The album spawned West's final US charting country songs: "What's Good for the Goose (Is Good for the Gander)", "Let Love Come Lookin' for You" and "We Know Better Now". A duet taken from Kenny Rogers' ''[[Duets (Kenny Rogers album)|Duets]]'' compilation ("[[Together Again (Buck Owens song)|Together Again]]") made the US country top 20 in 1984 as well.<ref name="Country Songs"/> In 1986, Permian closed its doors.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Permian Records Is Dissolved |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 20, 1986 |volume=98 |issue=51 |page=33 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=dottie+west+permian+records+just+dottie+1984&pg=PA33 |access-date=17 December 2023}}</ref>

In 1986, West made her film debut in the [[science fiction]] thriller ''[[The Aurora Encounter]]''. She played the role of Irene Rutherford, a widow who is visited by extra terrestrial creatures.<ref name="Aurora">{{cite book |last1=Green |first1=Paul |title=Encyclopedia of Weird Westerns Supernatural and Science Fiction Elements in Novels, Pulps, Comics, Films, Television and Games, 2d Ed. |date=2016 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=978-1476662572 |page=26}}</ref> The film was considered "low-budget" by critics.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Santa Clarita Valley Signal|Santa Clarita Signal]]|author=Williams, Jim|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/55677249/the-signal/|title=Comic Book Stuff Should Be Top Renter|date=August 1, 1986|page=38|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Albright |first1=Brian |title=Regional Horror Films, 1958-1990 A State-by-State Guide with Interviews |date=2012 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=978-1476600420 |page=296}}</ref> As the 1980s progressed, West's popularity declined and her concert offerings became more sporadic.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}}<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Among her professional engagements was occasional opportunities filling in as Kenny Rogers' duet partner when other female performers were unavailable.<ref name="Music City News"/> In 1989, she began working alongside her daughter [[Shelly West]], who had her own recording career during this time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prime |first1=John Andrew |title=Mon-Daughter-Pairing a First |work=[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Times]] |date=October 25, 1989}}</ref>

In 1990, West declared [[bankruptcy]] and divorced her third husband Alan Winters.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}} She continued to perform despite her personal challenges. West's booking agent Bobby Roberts booked her for 80 concert gigs during the course of 1990. She also appeared as a frequent guest on [[The Nashville Network]] and performed regularly on the ''Grand Ole Opry''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Dottie West Is Looking Though She's Down |journal=Music City News |date=September 1990 |page=18}}</ref> Shortly before her 1991 death, West was planning an album of duets with [[Tanya Tucker]] and [[Tammy Wynette]],<ref name="The Boot">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Gayle |title=Country Music Memories: Dottie West Dies |url=https://theboot.com/dottie-west-dies-dead/ |website=The Boot |date=September 4, 2023 |access-date=27 December 2023}}</ref> along with an autobiography.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>

==Death==
In July 1991, West lost control of a [[Chevrolet Camaro]] she was driving and crashed into a concrete wall. She was given a ticket for "careless driving" and for not wearing a seat belt.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=115}} A second car accident a month later would take her life.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}} On August 30, 1991, West was running late for a scheduled performance at the Grand Ole Opry. While driving herself to the venue, West's vehicle stalled. West then flagged down a passing driver, who happened to be her neighbor George Thackston. He agreed to drive her to the Opry.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=121}} While attempting to take the [[Opryland USA|Opryland]] highway exit ramp, Thackston lost control of the vehicle. The car then went airborne and hit an embankment.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=121-122}}<ref name="NY Times Crash">{{cite news |title=Crash Badly Injures a Country Music Star |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/01/us/crash-badly-injures-a-country-music-star.html |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 1, 1991}}</ref> It was later reported that Thackston had taken the 25 mile-per-hour exit ramp at an estimated speed of 55 miles per hour.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=121-122}}

Thackston was taken to the hospital in [[Medical state|critical condition]].<ref name="LA Times Crash">{{cite news |title=Country Singer Dottie West Hurt in Crash Near Opryland |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-09-01-mn-2572-story.html |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 1, 1991}}</ref> Thackston ultimately survived the crash. He was later charged with [[Endangerment|reckless endangerment]] and pleaded no contest. He was ultimately sentenced to 11 months [[probation]] and to complete an alcohol recovery program.<ref>{{cite news |title=Driver Gets Probation in Dottie West Crash |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-03-28-mn-4311-story.html |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 28, 1992}}</ref> At the scene of the accident, West did not appear to have any injuries. However, she was admitted to the hospital with a [[Splenic injury|ruptured spleen]] and a lacerated liver.<ref name="The Boot"/> Doctors also initially believed she might have been paralyzed. At [[Vanderbilt University Medical Center]], West underwent a 90-minute surgery and was then taken to the surgical intensive care unit.<ref name="LA Times Crash"/> West underwent a second operation but lost a significant amount of blood and doctors did not think she would survive.<ref>{{cite news |title=DOTTIE WEST NEAR DEATH, DOCTOR SAYS |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/1991/09/04/dottie-west-near-death-doctor-says/ |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 4, 1991}}</ref> On the morning of September 4, 1991, West was being prepared for her next surgery. However, her heart stopped on the operating table at 9:43 AM, and she was unable to be revived. She was 58 years old.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=122-123}}<ref>{{cite news |title=COUNTRY SINGER, COMPOSER DOTTIE WEST DIES AT 58 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1991/09/05/country-singer-composer-dottie-west-dies-at-58/e180c7ed-b6ee-4d63-9b72-31a676d8ff15/ |access-date=31 December 2023 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 4, 1991}}</ref>

West's [[funeral]] was held at Nashville's Christ Church on September 7, 1991.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dottie West Eulogized as Singer Who Touched Many |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-09-08-mn-3059-story.html |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 8, 1991}}</ref> West was honored by her granddaughters with an original song paying tribute to her, which was played at the funeral.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=124}} [[Steve Wariner]] sang "[[Amazing Grace]]" during the services. Kenny Rogers eulogized her in a speech: "When she sang about pain, she felt pain; when she sang about love, she felt love; when she sang about beauty, she felt that beauty. While some performers sang words, she sang emotions."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}} West was then buried at Mount View Cemetery in her hometown of McMinnville.<ref>{{cite news |title=Country music star Dottie West over the years |url=https://www.tennessean.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/music/2016/08/27/country-music-star-dottie-west-over-the-years/88837778/ |access-date=31 December 2023 |work=[[The Tennessean|Tennessean]] |date=August 26, 2016}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Marriages and children===
West was married and divorced three times.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Dottie West, 58 |magazine=[[The New York Times|New York Times Biographical Service]] |date=1991 |volume=22 |page=915}}</ref> Her first marriage was to Bill West in 1953, whom she met on her first day of classes at Tennessee Tech.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wanamaker |first1=Monty |last2=Keathley |first2=Chris |title=McMinnville |date=2009 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=978-1439637708}}</ref> The couple wed during her sophomore year and were pictured together in their 1953 college yearbook.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=76}} Bill was also a [[steel guitar]]ist who became a member of his wife's touring band and co-wrote many of her early songs.<ref name="Bill West">{{cite magazine |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Lifenotes: Musician and Audio Innovator Bill West Passes |magazine=[[MusicRow]] |date=September 23, 2013 |url=https://musicrow.com/2013/09/lifenotes-musician-and-audio-innovator-bill-west-passes/ |access-date=27 December 2023}}</ref> In their first years in Nashville, the Wests rented a pink cottage on the western side of the city.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=79}} A home they later bought in Nashville caught fire in 1969. The family then purchased a home located in the Greenhills neighborhood of Nashville.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=91}} In 1972, the West's divorced. Dottie later claimed that she caught Bill cheating on her.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=225}} Bill West later died in 2013.<ref name="Bill West"/>

The Wests had four children together by 1958: Morris, Kerry and [[Shelly West|Shelly]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Rumble |editor1-first=John |editor2-last=Kingsbury |editor2-first=Paul |title=The Encyclopedia of Country Music |date=1998 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0199770557 |page=578}}</ref> Their fourth child Dale was born in 1962.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=80}} The couple's children also became involved with the music business. Kerry West became an [[audio engineer]] and found employment running sound equipment during shows for [[Ronnie Milsap]]. Mo West was a songwriter and guitarist, notably for the American [[Rock music|rock]] band Thunder, which was briefly signed to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name="Bill West"/> Shelly West was a recording artist during the 1980s, topping the US country charts as a duet team with [[David Frizzell]] and as a solo artist.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mecir |first1=Petr |title=Shelly West: Something Was Very Special About Mom |url=https://countryzone.net/en/interviews/540-shelly-west-something-was-very-special-about-mom |website=Country Zone |access-date=27 December 2023}}</ref>

In 1972, West married her band's drummer Byron Metcalf. Metcalf was 12 years younger.<ref name="Opry Book"/> During their wedding ceremony, West changed the phrase "'til death do us part" to "as long as love shall last". When commenting on her new marriage, West said, "I'm attracted to younger men and I'm not afraid to admit it...I don't mind saying it. I have nothing to hide."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=225}} In 1980, West filed for divorce from Metcalf, citing his drinking and infidelity.<ref>{{Cite web|work=The Evening News |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1982&dat=19810407&id=UwJgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3G0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=2488,873316|title=Dottie wins divorce|agency=Associated Press|page=2A|date=April 7, 1981|access-date=October 28, 2023}}</ref> In 1981, the divorce became final. It was agreed that West would give Metcalf $55,000, along with $10,000 provided to Metcalf's lawyer. "I work. He doesn't," she told the press.<ref>{{cite news |last1=HANAUER |first1=JOAN |title=COUNTRY BLUES |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1981/04/07/COUNTRY-BLUES/2327355467600/ |access-date=27 December 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=April 7, 1981}}</ref> In 1983, West wed sound engineer Al Winters.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}} The couple had a 23-year age difference. In 1988, West filed for divorce, citing "irreconcilable differences" and "cruel and inhuman treatment".<ref>{{cite news |title=Singer Dottie West files for divorce |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1988/03/29/Singer-Dottie-West-files-for-divorce/8065575614800/ |access-date=27 December 2023 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=March 29, 1988}}</ref> Their divorce became final in January 1990.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}}

===Financial challenges and bankruptcy===
In her later years, West became known for her spending habits.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}}<ref name="Sun Sentinel"/><ref name="Seattle Times">{{cite news |title=Lee Plays Dottie West Role To Near Perfection |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950122&slug=2100664 |access-date=27 December 2023 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=January 22, 1995}}</ref> In some instances, stores would remain open through midnight so she could shop alone.<ref name="LA Times">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Ted |title=Focus : The Private Side of Dottie West |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-01-22-tv-23066-story.html |access-date=27 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 22, 1995}}</ref> "I can spend money real quick, I'm good at that. And there's been times that maybe I spent it in a way that I shouldn't. But I've always enjoyed it," she later commented.<ref name="Opry Book"/> By the 1980s, West was bringing in between one and two million dollars yearly.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=101}}<ref>{{cite news |title=SIX YEARS LATER, WEST'S FINAL ALBUM MAY GET A SECOND CHANCE |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/1991/12/02/six-years-later-wests-final-album-may-get-second-chance/ |access-date=30 December 2023 |work=[[Sun Sentinel]] |date=December 2, 1991}}</ref> During this period, West purchased a colonial mansion in [[Williamson County, Tennessee]]. The home was equipped with a [[bowling alley]], closets organized with designer clothes and a [[Nursery (room)|nursery]] for her two grandchildren.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=103-105}} West also had a mirror built on the ceiling above her master bed.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}}

In August 1990, West filed for [[chapter 11 bankruptcy]], owing the [[Internal Revenue Service|US Internal Revenue Service]] one million dollars.<ref>{{cite news |title=SHORT TAKES: Dottie West Files for Bankruptcy |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-08-21-ca-1345-story.html |access-date=30 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 21, 1990}}</ref> She later switched to chapter seven, which allowed her to liquidate her assets.<ref name="LarkinCountry"/> Her management company claimed West "breached" her contract and sued her for $130,000. Her former manager Michael Brokaw claimed that he was due 15 percent of her earnings and had yet to be paid. He sued her for $110,295.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=108}} In September 1990, the [[First American National Bank]] seized her colonial mansion after previously buying it for $800,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=SHORT TAKES: Country Singer to Quit Mansion |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-09-17-ca-744-story.html |access-date=30 December 2023 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 17, 1990}}</ref> Her [[Chevrolet Corvette]] was also seized and Kenny Rogers loaned her a car instead.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=226}} West then moved into Nashville's Wessex Towers [[condominium]]s.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=111}} Several months later, an unknown caller informed bankruptcy trustee John McLemore that West was secretly hiding personal possessions in storage to avoid being seized by the IRS. In April 1991, several porcelain objects and a guitar were found in a storage facility.<ref>{{cite news |title=BANKRUPTCY OFFICERS SEIZE SINGER'S EFFECTS |url=https://www.deseret.com/1991/4/1/18913279/bankruptcy-officers-seize-singer-s-effects |access-date=30 December 2023 |work=[[Deseret News]] |date=April 1, 1991}}</ref>

In June 1991, the IRS held a public [[auction]] where people bought West's personal possessions. Some fans bought items and returned them to West.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minnigh |first1=Bruce |title=AUCTION BRINGS TEARS, CASH |work=[[The Tennessean|Tennessean]] |date=June 14, 1991}}</ref> Items sold at the auction included West's [[piano|baby grand piano]] and her 1976 [[Cadillac Fleetwood]]. Despite the proceeds from the auction, West was still left with debt.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=115}}

==Artistry==
===Influences===
From an early age, West was routinely exposed to country music.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=20}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=222-223}} West's father routinely played the [[fiddle]] during her childhood. He often performed songs by [[Jimmie Rodgers]] on the instrument while West's mother would sing along.{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=20-21}} Because the family was one of few to own a radio, neighbors would gather at her childhood home every Saturday evening to listen to the [[Grand Ole Opry]].{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=52-53}} Among her earliest influences was the [[Carter Family]] and [[The Carter Sisters]].{{sfn|Berryhill|Meeker|p=54}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} West later commented that she would cry when hearing [[Anita Carter]]'s "pure sweet voice" in the family group.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ellison |first1=Curtis W. |title=Country Music Culture From Hard Times to Heaven |date=1995 |publisher=[[University of Mississippi|University of Mississippi Press]] |isbn=978-1604739343 |page=34}}</ref> She was most especially influenced by the group's matriarch, [[Mother Maybelle Carter]]. "She was very dedicated to her career, but she was also a very good mama. She really took care of those girls. I watched how she handled the business part, the stage, the performance, and the traveling."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}}

[[File:Patsy Cline 1960 publicity portrait - cropped.jpg|thumb|left|160px|West's biggest musical influence was [[Patsy Cline]], who served as both her friend and mentor.]]
West's most significant musical influence was [[Patsy Cline]]. While the pair also were friends, Cline also served as a mentor to West.<ref name="Medium"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barton |first1=Laura |title=Hard-working, hard-living, hard done by: How Patsy Cline epitomised the female country music star |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/patsy-cline-tribute-death-anniversary-b2290383.html |access-date=5 January 2024 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=March 4, 2023}}</ref> According to West, Cline took a "genuine interest" in her career,{{sfn|Nassour|p=137}} while also providing advice on her stage presence and vocal delivery.<ref name="Medium"/> "I think I was most influenced by Patsy Cline. She said things for people. There was so much feeling there. In fact she told me, 'Hoss, if you can't do it with feeling, don't'," she told writer [[Robert K. Oermann]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=223}} West sometimes attended Cline's [[Decca Records]] recording sessions and would observe her singing and performance style. She recalled her reaction after listening to one of Cline's playbacks after a session, "You know, afterward you're supposed to say something nice. I couldn't talk. I was dumbfounded."<ref name="Opry Book"/>

West sometimes worked the road with Cline.{{sfn|Nassour|p=137}} She played in what would be Cline's last performance on March 3, 1963 in [[Kansas City, Kansas]].<ref name="Plane Crash">{{cite web |title=Patsy Cline Performs Her Final Show |url=https://theboot.com/patsy-cline-final-show/ |website=The Boot |date=March 3, 2023 |access-date=6 January 2024}}</ref> Cline was scheduled to take an airplane alongside her road manager to Nashville, but was delayed due to poor weather conditions. Instead, she accepted an invitation from West to travel to Nashville by car. Cline was carrying her suitcase to West's car when she decided it would be faster to travel home by plane.{{sfn|Nassour|p=223}} Leaving instead on her manager's plane, Cline was killed in en route to Nashville on March 5.<ref name="Plane Crash"/> West recalled feeling traumatized by Cline's death. "I was sipping black coffee and saying, 'Damn it, Patsy, why didn't you come with us?," she told Cline's biographer Ellis Nassour.{{sfn|Nassour|p=238}} Until the end of her life, West kept a scrapbook given to her by Cline that was filled with mementos and memorabilia.{{sfn|Nassour|p=202}} Years later, West wrote the foreword to Cline's biography ''Honky Tonk Angel: The Intimate Story of Patsy Cline''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Honky Tonk Angel The Intimate Story of Patsy Cline By Ellis Nassour, Foreword by Dottie West |url=https://www.chicagoreviewpress.com/honky-tonk-angel-products-9781556527470.php |website=[[Chicago Review Press]] |access-date=6 January 2024}}</ref>{{sfn|Nassour|p=ix-xi}}

===Mentoring younger artists===
{{multiple image
| total_width = 290
| align  = right
| image1 = Steve wariner 2019 (cropped).jpg
| image2 = Larry Gatlin.JPG
| footer = West was known for discovering up-and-coming artists, notably [[Steve Wariner]] (left) and [[Larry Gatlin]] (right).
}}
West became known for discovering up-and-coming music artists and mentoring their early careers.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}}<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> She was among the first country artists to record songs by female writers. Her early albums featured songs written by [[Jessi Colter]], [[Sandy Mason]] and [[Jeannie Seely]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} West also recorded some of the early material Seely wrote,{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=301}} such as "It Just Takes Practice" and "Another Heart for You to Break".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''Dottie West Sings'' (Album Notes and Liner Notes) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=December 1965 |id=LSP-3490}}</ref><ref name="Suffer Time Liner Notes and Al"/> West and Seely also became close friends. The pair met at Los Angeles's [[Palomino Club (North Hollywood)|Palomino Club]] and encouraged her to move to Nashville. The pair also had a close friendship. "She was such a great friend. We called each other ‘Three O’Clock in the Morning Friends,’ because if you needed to talk to someone at three in the morning, you knew they would be willing to wake up and be there for you," Seely recalled.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Nicholson |first1=Jessica |title=Jeannie Seely Showcases Decades Of Friendships On New Album, 'An American Classic' |magazine=[[MusicRow]] |date=August 13, 2020 |url=https://musicrow.com/2020/08/jeannie-seely-showcases-decades-of-friendships-on-new-album-an-american-classic/ |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref>

West discovered [[Steve Wariner]], who would have a series of top ten country singles during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Country Music Memories: Steve Wariner Joins the Grand Ole Opry |url=https://theboot.com/steve-wariner-grand-ole-opry/ |website=The Boot |date=May 11, 2020 |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref> Seventeen year-old Wariner was performing at the Nashville Country Club in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]] when West interrupted his show to sing harmony with him.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Partridge |first1=Tamela Meredith |title=Stev Wariner at Little Opry |url=https://ourbrowncounty.com/2003-september/steve-wariner-at-little-opry/ |website=Our Brown County |date=September 2003 |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref> Wariner started playing [[Bass (instrument)|bass]] in West's band and toured with her during the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |title=STEVE WARINER |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/1987/11/15/steve-wariner-4/ |access-date=15 January 2024 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=November 15, 1987}}</ref> Wariner also lived with West at her Nashville home for several years. "I just grew up with Dottie West," Wariner recounted.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Beck |first1=Leon |title=STEVE WARINER BRAZORIA COUNTY FAIR OCT. 11 |magazine=Texas Hot Country Magazine |url=http://www.texashotcountrymagazine.com/articles/steve-wariner-brazoria-county-fair-oct-11 |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref> West also discovered [[Larry Gatlin]], who would also have a successful country recording career performing as "Larry Gatlin and the Gatlin Brothers". In the early 1970s, Gatlin went to Las Vegas to audition for the [[Gospel music|gospel]] group [[The Imperials]]. As he was walking through a showroom, he caught the attention of West. After having a conversation, Gatlin pitched several songs to West, two of which she later recorded ("You're the Other Half of Me" and "Once You Were Mine"). West also encouraged Gatlin to move to Nashville and bought him a plane ticket to the city.<ref>{{cite web |title=First Time Stories: Larry Gatlin |url=https://theboot.com/larry-gatlin-dottie-west-song/ |website=The Boot |date=March 16, 2017 |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref>

===Musical styles===
West's RCA recordings were largely identified with the [[Nashville Sound]] sub-genre of country music.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} The Nashville Sound was a style of country that replaced traditional production with more [[Pop music|pop]]-influenced instrumentation. Many Nashville Sound recordings featured orchestras, [[Jazz music|jazz]]-styled guitars and four-part harmonies.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Clifford Thompson |date=2020 |title=Contemporary World Musicians |publisher=Routledge |page= |isbn=9781135939618}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hubbs |first1=Nadine |title=Rednecks, Queers, and Country Music |date=2014 |publisher=[[University of California|University of California Press]] |isbn=978-0520280663 |page=8}}</ref> West's RCA producer Chet Atkins highlighted her songwriting and vocal delivery and backed it with Nashville Sound production to help make it commercially successful.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nash |first1=Alanna |title=Behind Closed Doors |date=2002 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Cooper Square Publishing LLC]] |isbn=978-0815412588 |page=40}}</ref> Authors Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann described West's RCA singles "Would You Hold It Against Me" and "Paper Mansions" as "definitive Nashville Sound hits".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=224}} As the Nashville Sound evolved into [[country pop]] style during the 1970s, so did West's music.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=355}} Tim Sheridan of [[AllMusic]] wrote, "There are all kinds of country music: hillbilly, bluegrass, honky-tonk, etc. Dottie West is the queen of Spandex country: a slickly produced Nashville brand of country-pop."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sheridan |first1=Tim |title=''Are You Happy Baby: The Collection'': Dottie West: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/are-you-happy-baby-collection-1976-1984-mw0000596774 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=7 January 2024}}</ref>

==Legacy, influence and achievements==
{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Dottie West}}

Dottie West was considered among several artists to elevate the platform of female country artists.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=222-226}} Robert K. Oermann compared West to that of Patsy Cline, [[Loretta Lynn]], [[Dolly Parton]] and [[Tammy Wynette]], saying, "these women were American icons whose songs were about heartache and resilience. They rose from poverty to become glittering heroines."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=TURNING THE HURT INTO HITS |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/03/18/turning-the-hurt-into-hits/0c9e4c2f-d38c-4a27-b39a-afd48dfb2f88/ |access-date=20 January 2024 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 18, 1995}}</ref> Jason Ankeny of [[AllMusic]] wrote, "West's battles for identity and respect within the male-dominated country music hierarchy were instrumental in enabling other female artists to gain control over the directions of their careers."<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Robert Hilburn of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote, "In the mid-’60s, she was one of the handful of singers, including Loretta Lynn, who helped demonstrate that females could compete on honky-tonk jukeboxes with the men who had previously dominated the field."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hilburn |first1=Robert |title=APPRECIATIONS : Dottie West's Country Music Legacy |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-09-05-ca-2505-story.html |access-date=20 January 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 5, 1991}}</ref>

West is also remembered for reinventing and continuing her career in her middle age. Juli Thanki of ''[[The Tennessean]]'' wrote, "West continually reinvented herself during her career, transforming from the gingham-clad girl next door to chart-topping country bombshell."<ref name="Tennessean"/> Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann found that West had a "highly successful comeback" in her forties by taking on a "glamorous new image" and wearing "eye-popping costumes".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=355-357}} Jason Ankeny found that West had more success in middle age due to the changing culture: "As the sexual revolution peaked, so did West's career; after the 1973 success of the crossover smash 'Country Sunshine,' written for Coca-Cola, her material became far more provocative and, much to the chagrin of country purists, more commercially successful as well."<ref name="autogenerated1"/>

In 1995, West's life and career were made into a [[television movie]] which aired on [[CBS]] titled ''[[Big Dreams and Broken Hearts: The Dottie West Story]]''. West was portrayed by actress [[Michele Lee]]. It also featured cameo appearances from Loretta Lynn, Dolly Parton, [[Willie Nelson]] and Kenny Rogers.<ref name="Variety">{{cite magazine |last1=Sandler |first1=Adams |title=Cbs Sunday Night Movie Big Dreams & Broken Hearts: The Dottie West Story |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 19, 1995 |url=https://variety.com/1995/tv/reviews/cbs-sunday-night-movie-big-dreams-broken-hearts-the-dottie-west-story-1200440014/ |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> The film was created by West's former manager Ken Kragen and Michele Lee. Lee wore many of West's original stage clothes and did her own research into West's past.<ref name="LA Times"/> ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' commented positively on Lee's singing performances for the film: "Some of the best moments in this generally entertaining movie feature Lee's impersonations of West's legendary performances."<ref>{{cite news |title=Lee Plays Dottie West Role To Near Perfection |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950122&slug=2100664 |access-date=21 January 2024 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=January 22, 1995}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the director's role in the film: "Director Bill D’Elia has a talented cast and successfully guides them in establishing a high credibility factor to the story usually lacking in other biopix."<ref name="Variety"/>

In 1999, West returned to the public consciousness when [[Jo Dee Messina]] covered her number one single "[[Lesson in Leavin']]".<ref name="Messina">{{cite magazine |title=THEY'RE PLAYING MY SONG |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=May 29, 1999 |volume=111 |issue=22 |page=38 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mg0EAAAAMBAJ&dq=jo+dee+messina+dottie+west+lesson+in+leavin+billboard&pg=PA38 |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> A fan of West's music, Messina was inspired to record the song after watching her 1995 television movie.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Dauphin |first1=Chuck |title=Watch Jo Dee Messina's Acoustic Take on Her Classic Dottie West Cover 'Lesson In Leavin": Exclusive Premiere |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/country/jo-dee-messinas-lesson-in-leavin-acoustic-exclusive-premiere-6670997/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> In reference to West's legacy, Messina told ''Billboard'', "She had spunk. She had fire. She loved the fans, and she loved people. She was a very strong woman."<ref name="Messina"/>

In 2002, West was named among [[CMT (American TV channel)|CMT]]'s "40 Greatest Women of Country Music", a special which ran on the network during the year.<ref>{{cite news |title='40 Greatest Women' Announced |url=https://www.cmt.com/news/whj8kx/40-greatest-women-announced |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221206010837/https://www.cmt.com/news/whj8kx/40-greatest-women-announced |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 6, 2022 |access-date=21 January 2024 |work=[[CMT (American TV channel)|CMT]] |date=August 28, 2002}}</ref> West's hometown of [[McMinnville, Tennessee]], dedicated [[Tennessee State Route 56|Highway 56]] to her memory, naming it the Dottie West Memorial Highway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/memorial-built-memory-dottie-west-171108902.html|title=Memorial Built In Memory Of Dottie West|website=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=August 31, 2016|access-date=December 29, 2022}}</ref>

In the 2010s, Jeannie Seely and Ron Harman began an effort to induct West into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]]. Harman created a [[Facebook]] page in 2012 to bring attention to the campaign, which was titled "Dottie West Needs Inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame". More than 15,000 users "liked" the page.<ref name="Tennessean"/> In 2014, Steve Wariner wrote an [[op-ed]] for ''Billboard'' magazine citing his reasons for why West should be inducted into the Hall of Fame as well: "In my humble opinion, Dottie helped build the template for the modern day country girl singer. She was a true pioneer."<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Wariner |first1=Steve |title=Op-Ed: Steve Wariner on Why Dottie West Should Be a Country Music Hall of Fame Member |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 21, 2014 |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/op-ed-steve-wariner-on-why-dottie-west-should-be-a-country-music-hall-of-fame/ |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> In March 2018, it was officially announced that West would be inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Betts |first1=Stephen L. |title=Dottie West, Ricky Skaggs Set for Country Music Hall of Fame |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=March 27, 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/dottie-west-ricky-skaggs-set-for-country-music-hall-of-fame-205466/ |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> In October 2018, West was inducted through the Hall of Fame's official ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Country Music Hall of Fame Welcomes Ricky Skaggs, Dottie West, Johnny Gimble |url=https://www.cmt.com/news/crbub1/country-music-hall-of-fame-welcomes-ricky-skaggs-dottie-west-johnny-gimble |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230814191139/https://www.cmt.com/news/crbub1/country-music-hall-of-fame-welcomes-ricky-skaggs-dottie-west-johnny-gimble |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 14, 2023 |access-date=21 January 2024 |work=[[CMT (American TV channel)|CMT]] |date=October 22, 2018}}</ref>

